# DockManage Cursor Rules

## General Rules

- Always write clean, readable, and modular code
- Prefer simplicity over abstraction
- Avoid unnecessary complexity
- Keep functions small (ideally under 50 lines)
- Use meaningful variable and function names

---

## Backend Rules (Node.js / Express)

- Use Express for all APIs
- Use async/await (no callbacks or .then chains)
- Handle errors properly with try/catch
- Return consistent JSON responses

- All routes must be prefixed with /api
- Do not expose Docker socket directly to clients

- Use dockerode for all Docker interactions
- Do NOT use shell commands like exec("docker ...")

Example response format:
{
  "success": true,
  "data": ...
}

Error format:
{
  "success": false,
  "error": "message"
}

---

## Frontend Rules (React)

- Use functional components only
- Use React hooks (useState, useEffect)
- Keep components small and reusable
- Avoid deeply nested components

- Use axios for API calls
- Use relative API paths (/api/...)

---

## UI Rules

- Use Tailwind CSS for styling
- Use shadcn/ui components wherever possible
- Maintain consistent spacing (p-4, gap-4, etc.)

- Default to dark mode
- Use clear visual hierarchy

Status colors:
- running → green
- stopped → red
- restarting → yellow

---

## Logs Viewer Rules

- Display logs in a scrollable container
- Use monospace font
- Use dark background
- Auto-scroll on new logs

---

## Code Style

- Prefer early returns over nested conditions
- Avoid long files (>300 lines)
- Split logic into separate modules when needed

---

## Architecture Rules

- Single service architecture
- Backend serves frontend static files
- API routes under /api
- No microservices

---

## When Generating Code

- Only modify what is requested
- Do not rewrite entire files unless explicitly asked
- Keep existing structure intact

---

## When Unsure

- Ask for clarification instead of guessing
- Or provide 2 possible approaches and explain tradeoffs

---

## Performance

- Avoid unnecessary re-renders in React
- Avoid blocking operations in backend

---

## Security

- Always validate inputs
- Add basic authentication to protected routes
- Never expose sensitive system paths

---

## Priority

1. Working code
2. Readable code
3. Clean structure
4. Optimization (only if needed)